<p> The waveguide, a slab of material of thickness <i >d</i> and index of refraction <i >n</i><sub>1</sub>, is sandwiched between two media, the cladding, of index of refraction <i>n</i><sub>2</sub>. The wavelengths of the
light in the two media are, respectively, <!-- MP EQ( --><script>
	MPSetEqnAttrs('eq0006','',3,[[45,12,3,-1,-1],[61,16,4,-1,-1],[76,20,5,-1,-1],[69,19,5,-1,-1],[92,24,6,-1,-1],[115,31,8,-2,-2],[190,52,14,-3,-3]]);
	MPEquation();</script><!-- )MP EQ --> and <!-- MP EQ( --><script>
	MPSetEqnAttrs('eq0007','',3,[[48,12,3,-1,-1],[64,16,4,-1,-1],[80,20,5,-1,-1],[72,19,5,-1,-1],[96,24,6,-1,-1],[120,31,8,-2,-2],[200,52,14,-3,-3]]);
	MPEquation();</script><!-- )MP EQ -->,
where <!-- MP EQ( --><script>
	MPSetEqnAttrs('eq0008','',3,[[54,12,3,-1,-1],[73,16,4,-1,-1],[92,20,5,-1,-1],[83,19,5,-1,-1],[109,24,6,-1,-1],[135,31,8,-2,-2],[222,51,13,-3,-3]]);
	MPEquation();</script><!-- )MP EQ --> is the wavelength of the light in vacuum. The
corresponding angular wave numbers are <!-- MP EQ( --><script>
	MPSetEqnAttrs('eq0009','',3,[[48,12,3,-1,-1],[65,16,4,-1,-1],[80,20,5,-1,-1],[72,19,5,-1,-1],[96,24,6,-1,-1],[120,31,8,-2,-2],[200,52,14,-3,-3]]);
	MPEquation();</script><!-- )MP EQ --> and <!-- MP EQ( --><script>
	MPSetEqnAttrs('eq0010','',3,[[50,12,3,-1,-1],[67,16,4,-1,-1],[84,20,5,-1,-1],[74,19,5,-1,-1],[101,24,6,-1,-1],[126,31,8,-2,-2],[209,52,14,-3,-3]]);
	MPEquation();</script><!-- )MP EQ -->.</p>

<p>We are interested in the guided modes for this waveguide. The guided modes are the solutions of Maxwell€™s equations (plus the appropriate boundary conditions) that correspond to traveling waves in the waveguide and evanescent waves in the cladding. In terms of a ray picture, this means that each ray inside the waveguide undergoes total internal reflection at the core-cladding boundary.</p>

<p>It can be shown in the literature<sup>1,2</sup> that for a given parameter set (<i ><span style='font-family:Symbol'>w</span></i>, <i >n</i><sub>1</sub>,<i > n</i><sub>2</sub>, and <i >d</i>) there exist <i >M</i> such modes, where</p>

