  </tr>
</table></center></div>

<p>It turns out that inside the waveguide the electric field of each mode is a superposition of two plane wave fields, one with the wave vector
<!-- MP EQ( --><script>
	MPSetEqnAttrs('eq0012','',3,[[114,14,4,-1,-1],[153,18,5,-1,-1],[192,23,7,-1,-1],[172,21,7,-1,-1],[230,27,8,-1,-1],[287,34,10,-2,-2],[479,59,17,-3,-3]]);
	MPEquation();</script><!-- )MP EQ --> and the other <!-- MP EQ( --><script>
	MPSetEqnAttrs('eq0013','',3,[[121,14,4,-1,-1],[163,18,5,-1,-1],[204,23,7,-1,-1],[183,21,7,-1,-1],[244,27,8,-1,-1],[305,34,10,-2,-2],[508,59,17,-3,-3]]);
	MPEquation();</script><!-- )MP EQ -->,
where <i ><span style='font-family:Symbol;'>q</span></i> is the "bounce" angle depicted in Fig. 2. In order for the field to be a mode, the bounce angle must
be a solution of the transcendental equation</p>
