<p class=MsoNormal>It can be shown from Eqs. (8) and (9) that the waves in the cladding decay exponentially away from the surfaces.</p>



<p><big><font color="#008040"><b>Evanescent Waves</b></font></big></p>
<p class=MsoNormal>The exponentially decaying waves present for both even and
odd modes are the evanescent waves in the cladding. The decay rate, <i><span style=font-family:symbol>g</span><sub>m</sub></i>, is the extinction coefficient of the evanescent wave.  Eq.
(6) shows that the decay rate depends on the propagation constant, <i><span style=font-family:symbol>b</span><sub>m</sub></i>, which depends on <i><span style=font-family:symbol>q</span><sub>m</sub></i> and the mode number, <i>m</i>. 
As the mode number increases, <i ><span style=font-family:symbol>q</span><sub>m</sub></i>, cos <i ><span style=font-family:symbol>q</span><sub>m</sub></i> and <i><span style=font-family:symbol>b</span><sub>m</sub></i> also increase while <i><span style=font-family:symbol>g</span><sub>m</sub></i> decreases. This results in
higher order modes penetrating further into the cladding of the waveguide.  This is illustrated in Example 4. </p>

